FIC FIC-G0Y-004 -0.05 "8 Thank you, said Louise. It's exactly what I need. However did you guess? Mind, God knows why I keep on recording the children for posterity, the way they are now. When I look back I could weep  dear little things tottering about on beaches. Phil hasn't addressed a civil word to us in weeks. Anyway  thanks. It's from Edward too. I took that as read. Since when did Edward go shopping on his own behalf? Where is he, anyway? In the Britches, I think. He's been trying to do something about the brambles and nettles. Louise flopped on to the sofa. How did you enjoy your day in London? It had its moments, said Helen evasively. What about the investment people? They made it fairly clear we were too small fry for them. And the place was more like a botanical gardens than an office. Tim knows some other people. I'll tell him to No, said Helen. We have still to recover from those. Think about it, conceded Louise. So what did you do after that  it can't have taken you all day? We had lunch in that restaurant in South Kensington. It doesn't exist any more. Exactly, said Helen. So we discovered. We had lunch on its ashes, as it were. Then we went shopping. Well! Quite a spree! Very good for you both. Don't patronise, said Helen. We're less socially disadvantaged than you imagine. The village provides resources undreamed of in Camden Town. Though I will admit that I find London disconcerting these days. The landscape. Everything  seems to be built of mirrors  what on earth has happened to brick? But I grant you that I'm behind the times in some ways. Architecture and offices full of botanical specimens are the least of it. Social etiquette, for instance What's done and what isn't. She shot her sister a crafty glance. Most of it is quite irrelevant to me, of course, but one keeps a sort of technical interest. Huh? said Louise. What are you blathering on about? Oh, I don't know How people behave Men and women, for instance. Such as Do women take the initiativ